{\b0\i0\fs24
Cloud Applications - Migration & Workload Management
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li200
**Conventional Migration (Lift-and-Shift)**

- Move an on-prem monolithic app (single server + local DB) to cloud.
- Limitation: basic lift-and-shift may not fully utilize cloud scalability or redundancy.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
{\b0\i0\fs24
Workload Categories & Cloud Scaling
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Static Workload
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
- Steady, predictable usage; minimal scaling.
- Example: internal HR system in a Colombo office.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Periodic Workload
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
- Predictable peaks like daily payroll and university exam portal traffic
- Pay-per-use and decommission unused resources in public cloud.
- Private cloud must maintain static scaling for peaks.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Once-in-a-Lifetime Workload
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
- Rare, massive spikes like Black Friday or New Year
- Manual provisioning works due to rarity; still pay-per-use.
- Resource pooling improves utilization.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Continuously Changing Workload
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
- Growing or shrinking usage like IoT data from Colombo traffic sensors.
- Requires continuous monitoring and incremental provisioning.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Unpredictable Workload
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
- Random traffic surges.
- Requires reactive auto-scaling with real-time monitoring.
- Challenges: fast reaction time; standby resources may be needed for extreme surges.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
{\b0\i0\fs24
Scaling Policies
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\fs20
Target Tracking Scaling
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
- Keeps a specific metric like CPU usage or memory usage at a target level.

**Cloud example**: Target CPU = 50%.

CPU rises to 65% \u8594\'3f cloud automatically adds more instances.

CPU drops to 35% \u8594\'3f cloud removes some instances.

- Ideal for apps with moderate, predictable fluctuations, like an e-commerce site in Sri Lanka during normal days.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\fs20
Step Scaling
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Adds or removes resources in steps depending on how far the metric is from the threshold.

**Cloud Example:** CPU usage:

o\u160\'3f70\u8211\'3f80% \u8594\'3f add 1 instance

o\u160\'3f80\u8211\'3f90% \u8594\'3f add 2 instances

o\u160\'3f90% \u8594\'3f add 4 instances

o\u160\'3fIf CPU drops below 90% for 5 minutes \u8594\'3f remove 4 instances

- Useful for sites with sudden but measurable spikes, like a Sri Lankan lottery results website on draw days.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\fs20
Simple Scaling
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Performs one scaling action for each alarm.

**Cloud Example**: CloudWatch alarm:

- CPU &gt; 70% triggers adding 2 instances
- CPU &lt; 30% triggers removing 1 instance
- Cooldown = 300 seconds.

Basic apps with occasional spikes where you don\u8217\'3ft need complex scaling logic.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\fs20
Scheduled Scaling
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Changes instance count at specific times.

**Cloud Example**:

- 8:00 AM \u8594\'3f scale up to 10 instances
- 6:00 PM \u8594\'3f scale down to 3 instances

Perfect for predictable traffic, like Government office systems in Sri Lanka during business hours.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b\fs20
Predictive Scaling
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Uses machine learning to forecast traffic and scale before spikes occur.

**Example**:

- Traffic usually peaks at 9 AM \u8594\'3f ASG adds instances at 8:45 AM automatically.

Apps with recurring peak patterns, like online university registration systems in Sri Lanka.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
{\b0\i0\fs24
Workload Types vs Scaling Policy
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
**Static Workload** \u8211\'3f No Scaling Needed
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
**Periodic Workload** \u8211\'3f Scheduled + Target Tracking or Step Scaling
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\fs20
**Once-in-a-Lifetime Workload **\u8211\'3f Scheduled + Target Tracking/Step Scaling
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
**Continuously Changing Workload **\u8211\'3f Target Tracking or Step Scaling
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
**Unpredictable Workload** \u8211\'3f Predictive + Target Tracking
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
{\b0\i0\fs24
Instance Termination Policies (Scale In)
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
When an Auto Scaling Group (ASG) needs to remove instances to scale in (reduce resources), you can control which EC2 instances get terminated first using termination policies.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
OldestInstance
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Terminates the instance that has been running the longest.

Replace old servers with newer ones.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
NewestInstance
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Terminates the most recently launched instance first.

Protect stable instances, remove new ones that may not be fully warmed up.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
OldestLaunchConfiguration
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Terminates instances using the oldest launch configuration first.

Ensure all instances run the latest configuration.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
OldestLaunchTemplate
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Removes instances from the oldest template first.

Keep fleet consistent with newest template versions.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
ClosestToBillingHour
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Terminates instances that are closest to the end of their current billing hour.

Optimize costs by avoiding partial-hour charges.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
{\b0\i0\fs24
Warm Pools for Auto Scaling Groups (ASG)
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
A Warm Pool is a collection of EC2 instances that are pre-initialized and ready to go, but not actively serving traffic yet.

Using a warm pool lets the ASG scale out faster because these instances are already partially ready.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
{\b0\i0\fs24
Auto Scaling Groups (ASG) - Horizontal Scaling & Data Handling
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
- Logical group of EC2 instances managed together.
- Scales in/out automatically to maintain availability and handle variable demand.
- Integrates with CloudWatch metrics, alarms, and load balancers.
- Can span multiple Availability Zones.

**Core ASG Components**

- Launch Template/Configuration: AMI, instance type, security groups, scripts.
- Capacity Settings: min, max, desired instances.
- Health Checks: automatically replace unhealthy instances.
- Scaling Policies: dynamic, scheduled, predictive.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Horizontal Scaling Only
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
ASGs add or remove EC2 instances, never modify

Vertical Scaling Not Supported

For bigger workloads, you scale by number of instances, not individual instance capacity
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Managing Data Stores During Scaling
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Ideal Microservices: Each service has its own isolated datastore \u8594\'3f easy to scale.

Services may share databases or file systems. Scaling compute alone doesn\u8217\'3ft solve data bottlenecks.

Therefore;

- Decouple Compute and Storage:
- Use managed databases (RDS, DynamoDB).
- Store static assets in object storage (S3, Azure Blob).
- Shared file systems (EFS) for multi-instance access.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Handling Database Write Load & Consistency
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
Scaling compute doesn\u8217\'3ft automatically solve write-heavy databases or consistency issues.

Use event-driven / asynchronous patterns:

- Buffer writes via Message Queues (SQS) or Streaming Systems (Kafka).
- Background workers process writes at a safe pace.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
{\b0\i0\fs24
SQS
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
**Ordering**\u160\'3f: Strong ordering within partitions

Message Replay

**Message Retention**\u160\'3f: Long, configurable

**Throughput**\u160\'3f: Extremely high

**Operational Complexity**\u160\'3f: High
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
{\b0\i0\fs24
Kafka
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
**Ordering**\u160\'3f: Standard: no ordering; FIFO: strict

No Message Replay

**Message Retention**\u160\'3f: Short, CSP-defined

**Throughput**\u160\'3f: Moderate

**Operational Complexity**\u160\'3f: Very low
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Takeaways
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
ASG is about adding/removing instances.

Data architecture must be decoupled from compute.

Event-driven patterns keep databases safe and consistent during scaling.

Choose SQS if you want simplicity, Kafka if you need high throughput + replay + ordering.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li200
{\b0\i0\fs24
Cloud Deployment Models
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
{\b0\i0\fs24
Private Cloud
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
**Definition:**
Cloud infrastructure used **only by one organization** (not shared).

**Features**

- Used by multiple departments
- Managed by organization / third party / cloud provider
- Can be **on-premise or off-premise**

**Infrastructure**

- **Homogeneous** \u8211\'3f same hardware
- **Heterogeneous** \u8211\'3f different hardware

**Policies**

- Fully customizable for the organization

**Cost**

- **CapEx** \u8211\'3f buy infrastructure
- **OpEx** \u8211\'3f pay as a service
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Private Cloud Deployments
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
**Outsourced Private Cloud**

- Infrastructure hosted by a **cloud provider**
- Used by **one organization only**

**Resource Sharing**

- CPU and RAM may be shared
- Isolation provided using **virtualization**

**Example**

- Amazon Web Services private cloud solutions

**Infrastructure Structure**

- Cloud infrastructure divided into **Regions** and **Availability Zones**
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Region
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
**Definition:**
A **Region** is a large geographic area with **multiple datacenters**.

**Characteristics**

- Regions are **300 km or more apart**
- Connected through the **cloud provider\u8217\'3fs private global network**
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
{\b0\i0\fs24
Reasons for choosing a region
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
**Compliance**

- Some countries require **data to stay in specific locations** (e.g., GDPR)

**Latency**

- Choose **regions closer to users** for faster response
- Example: **online gaming needs low latency**

**Service Availability**

- Some services exist **only in certain regions**
- Example: **special GPU servers**

**Pricing**

- **Costs vary between regions**
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1000
{\b0\i0\fs24
Compliance
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1000
{\b0\i0\fs24
Latency
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1000
{\b0\i0\fs24
Service Availability
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1000
{\b0\i0\fs24
Pricing
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Availability Zones (AZ)
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
**Definition**
An **Availability Zone** is an **isolated location inside a region**.

**Characteristics**

- Usually **3 or more datacenters**
- About **100 km apart**
- Connected by **high-speed private networks**

**Purpose**

- **High availability**
- **Disaster recovery**

**Example**
Applications run servers in **multiple AZs** so if one datacenter fails, another continues service.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Virtual Private Cloud (VPC)
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
**Definition**
A **VPC** is a **logically isolated network** inside a cloud provider\u8217\'3fs infrastructure.

**Key Idea**

- Hardware may be **shared**
- Network environment remains **isolated and private**
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
{\b0\i0\fs24
Features
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
**IP Address Range**

- Defined using **CIDR blocks**
- Example: **10.0.0.0/16**

**Subnets**

- Network segments inside a VPC
- **Public subnet** \u8211\'3f internet accessible
- **Private subnet** \u8211\'3f not directly accessible

**Route Tables**

- Control **how traffic moves between networks**
- Applied at **subnet level**

**Gateways**

**Internet Gateway**

- Allows **public subnet access to the internet**

**NAT Gateway**

- Allows **private subnet servers to access the internet securely** without being exposed
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1000
{\b0\i0\fs24
IP Address Range
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1000
{\b0\i0\fs24
Subnets
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1200
{\b0\i0\fs24
Public subnet
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1200
{\b0\i0\fs24
Private subnet
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1000
{\b0\i0\fs24
Route Tables
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1000
{\b0\i0\fs24
Gateways
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1200
{\b0\i0\fs24
Internet Gateway
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li1200
{\b0\i0\fs24
NAT Gateway
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Security Controls
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
**Security Group**

- Applied to **instances**
- **Allow rules only**
- **Stateful**
- **All rules evaluated**

**NACL**

- Applied to **subnets**
- **Allow &amp; Deny rules**
- **Stateless**
- **Rules checked in order**

**Easy Way to Remember**

- **Security Group \u8594\'3f Instance firewall**
- **NACL \u8594\'3f Subnet firewall**
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
{\b0\i0\fs24
Security Groups
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
**Definition**
A **Security Group** is a **virtual firewall for cloud instances**.

**Rules**

- Applied at **instance or network interface level**
- **Stateful** \u8594\'3f responses are automatically allowed
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
{\b0\i0\fs24
Network ACL (NACL)
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
**Definition**
A **Network ACL** is a **firewall applied at the subnet level**.

**Rules**

- **Stateless**
- Must explicitly define **allow or deny rules**
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
{\b0\i0\fs24
Virtual Private Network (VPN)
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li400
### **Definition**
A **VPN (Virtual Private Network)** creates a **secure connection over the internet**.

**Tunnel Concept**

- A **tunnel** is a virtual communication path
- Original packet is **encapsulated inside another packet**
- Data is **sent securely through the network**
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Types of VPN
}
\par\pard\plain
\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
{\b0\i0\fs24
Host-to-Host VPN
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
**Definition**
A **Host-to-Host VPN** creates a **secure connection between two devices**.

**Example**

- Employee **laptop connecting to the company network** securely.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
{\b0\i0\fs24
Site-to-Site VPN
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
**Definition**
A **Site-to-Site VPN** creates a **secure connection between two office networks**.

**Example**

- A company **connecting two branch offices securely**.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
VPN and Extended LAN
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
**Definition**
An **Extended LAN** allows **multiple remote networks to behave like one LAN**.

**How**

- Achieved using a **VPN tunnel**

**Example**

- Offices in **Colombo** and **Kandy**
- Same network: **192.168.1.0/24**
- VPN **Layer-2 extension** makes both appear as **one local network**.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
{\b0\i0\fs24
Latency Problem in Cloud Regions
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li600
**Concept**
If users access a **distant datacenter**, **latency increases**.

**Example Applications**

- **Online gaming**
- **AR/VR systems**

These require **very low latency for real-time performance**.
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
{\b0\i0\fs24
Local Zones
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
**Definition**
**Local Zones** place **cloud resources closer to major population centers**.

**Resources**

- Compute
- Storage
- Databases

**Purpose**

- **Reduce latency** for faster response times

**Note**

- Managed by the **cloud provider**
- **Not available in every region**
\par\pard\plain}
\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
{\b0\i0\fs24
Wavelength Zones
}
\par\pard\plain
{\slmult0\ltrpar\li800
**Definition**
**Wavelength Zones** place **cloud infrastructure inside telecom carrier networks**.

**Focus**

- **Ultra-low latency** for mobile applications

**Examples**

- **5G applications**
- **AR/VR**
- **Real-time gaming**

**Architecture**

- **Latency-critical components run in the Wavelength Zone**
- **Databases and storage remain in the main region**
